{
  "texts": [
    "Cognitive Offloading: For an agent, S, and her intentional action φ, on an external resource, R, S offloads cognition onto R, iff φ produces some change in R, and by φ-ing S is also ψ-ing, and ψ is a cognitive task that constitutively depends on those changes in R.",
    "Now, what the argument of (§3.3) envisions is that the events that constitute changes in R also constitute the agent's (cognitive) action.",
    "But this is just what Davidson thinks we should deny.",
    "Actions, on his model, are subject to what I'll call the Strict Bodily Constraint: Strict Bodily Constraint: If an event is an intentional action, then it is a movement of an agent's body; and if an event is not a movement of an agent's body, then it is not an intentional action.",
    "The consequences for HEC of Davidson's Strict Bodily Constraint come out most clearly in his discussion of complex actions."
  ]
}